            Your ratio of <strong class="font-medium">LH to FSH</strong> is elevated (2.81) and your <strong class="font-medium">AMH</strong> is high, which are classic blood-work indicators of <strong class="text-primary font-medium">Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)</strong>. The elevated <strong class="font-medium">Fasting Insulin</strong> (18.5) strongly suggests underlying insulin resistance. Insulin resistance prevents cells from absorbing glucose efficiently, causing the ovaries to produce excess androgens, leading to irregular cycles, acne, and weight retention.
